  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Biomedical Resources Grant: Harmonisation and Sharing of Linked HIV Cohort Data from Communities and Clinics in Africa</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1) The new data resource will bridge population-based HIV surveillance in the network for Analysing Longitudinal Population-based HIV data in Africa (ALPHA) and clinical monitoring in the network for International Epidemiologic Databases to Evaluate AIDS (IeDEA), ensuring that data on people who participate in both ALPHA and IeDEA cohorts is exchangable and shared across the two networks. HIV clinics serving ALPHA sites but not currently part of IeDEA will be supported to attain data management standards required for IeDEA membership, using the international standard HIV Cohort Data Exchange Protocol (HICDEP) to ensure global data comparability. 2) The resource will provide robust, population-based data for all stages of the HIV care continuum from infection to viral suppression, enabling empirical monitoring of all three UNAIDS 90-90-90 goals, which neither network can do independently. It will automate and document the creation of standardised analytical datasets, extending the Centre-in-a-box methodology pioneered by the INDEPTH network. Data integration software will build and document transformations for compiling each site&#x2019;s data into harmonised formats required for pooled datasets. Key summary statistical updates will be disseminated regularly through ALPHA web pages. Pooled datasets will be archived in the INDEPTH &quot;iShare&quot; public repository using the Data Documentation Initiative standard.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The UK Department of Health and Social Care (DHSC) funds outstanding global health research through the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR). The NIHR is providing support to a grant awarded under the Wellcome Trust&apos;s Biomedical Resources programme looking at the harmonisation and sharing of linked HIV cohort data from communities and clinics in Africa.</narrative>
  </description>
